title: Version diff tooling
body:
Currently we only show rows added in diffing from manual left join.
Having to write a query is still kind of cumbersome, and also requires knowing a primary key column.

We could:

1. In python to hide similar duckdb queries to produce data diffs (rows added, updated, removed. Columns added, updated, removed). Again the row diffing requires a key column here.
2. Write C++ code to iterate through manifests to produce an exact diff

Also, we can build a visualization tool to visualize the diff.

title: Make API for importing dataset less verbose
body:
Currently we require users to proxy through arrow APIs to create a dataset from a DataFrame or Parquet file.

i.e. 

```python
import pyarrow as pa

# Import a pandas DataFrame to Lance
tbl = pa.Table.from_pandas(my_dataframe)
lance.write_dataset(tbl, '/tmp/my_dataframe.lance')

# Import a Parquet file to Lance
parquet_dataset = ds.dataset('/tmp/hello.parquet')
lance.write_dataset(parquet_dataset, '/tmp/hello.lance')
```

It's preferred to hide this away and make it as simple as possible

title: [RUST] Store manifest metadata out of protobuf
body: Giving that we could allow to store arbitrary size of metadata key-value stores in manifest protobuf. We should consider to move it out of the `Manifest` protobuf body.  So that for most of the query/scans, we don't need to pay the latency of reading large k/v pairs.

title: [C++] Partitioning Support
body:
Should we use iceberg style partitioning, which is, the partitioning expression is stored in the manifest/fragment metadata, instead of a hive partitioning-style directory structure?

The logic is more complicated, but it makes schema/partitioning evolution easier without moving data. Also storing them in the same file might have performance benefits w.r.t. of cloud storage I/Os.
